// jblock — MONTHLY REPORT
//
// Controls: Store (required), Month Period (anchor month, DEFAULTS TO LAST
// MONTH, not the current month). Window is FIXED at the trailing 6 months
// from that anchor throughout this report.
//
// 1. TOTAL SALES TREND — plain inline SVG bar chart (no charting library
//    assumed available), store-wide monthly quantity, oldest→newest LEFT
//    TO RIGHT — the one place in this report that reads chronologically
//    forward; every table elsewhere reads most-recent-first.
//
// 2/3/4. SALES BY MODEL / PRODUCT / VARIANT — Total + 6 month-columns,
//    grand-total row pinned at top. Sortable: click "Total" or any month
//    header to sort by that column (click again to flip asc/desc).
//    DEFAULT sort is by the Month Period column (follows whichever month
//    you pick until you manually click a different column). More than 10
//    rows → top 10 shown + "Show all (N)" button.
//    Model and Product tables: the CHOSEN month's column (only that one,
//    not all 6) gets a ⚠ warning if that row had at least one OOS variant
//    as of Month Period's end. Rows are also CLICKABLE — opens the same
//    drill-down drawer used by Need Restock/Rotation (see below). Variant
//    table has neither — no OOS warning, no click-through (a "size" being
//    OOS across every product sharing it is a different, rarer question,
//    and there's no single product to drill into for a size).
//
//    Below Model and Product tables: RISING / DECLINING summaries, shown
//    SIDE BY SIDE on wide screens (flex-wrap, so it naturally stacks on
//    narrow ones instead of needing separate mobile/desktop logic). Rows
//    are also clickable, same drawer.
//
// 5. NEED RESTOCK / 6. PRODUCT ROTATION — Need Restock ranks by MISSED
//    SALES OPPORTUNITY (see below, no longer "currently OOS ranked by
//    importance"); Product Rotation is worst 6-month sellers ranked
//    ascending, but now REQUIRES A MINIMUM 3-MONTH TRIAL: a product must
//    have its earliest record (first sale or stock-ledger entry) before
//    the 1st of the month immediately preceding Month Period — e.g. for
//    a June anchor, before May 1st, guaranteeing at least 3 calendar
//    months of history (Apr/May/Jun) by the end of the window — anything
//    newer is excluded from Rotation entirely so brand-new products
//    aren't flagged for dropping before they've had a fair chance. Rows
//    clickable on both, opens the per-size drill-down drawer.
//
// DRILL-DOWN DRAWER — two modes:
//    Product (clicked a product row, or a Rising/Declining Product row, or
//      a Need Restock/Rotation row): ONE product's per-size breakdown.
//    Model (clicked a model row, or a Rising/Declining Model row): ALL
//      products under that model, ranked by their own sales in the
//      displayed window (bestseller first), each shown as its own
//      identical per-product block — same shape as Product mode, just
//      repeated. Capped at 25 products with a note if truncated.
//    Inside this drawer specifically, months run OLDEST→NEWEST left to
//    right — same deliberate exception as the trend chart, and as
//    established for this drawer previously.
//    Summary header per product block shows Current (End) Stock AND
//    Total Sales for the 6-month window, side by side.
//    Per-month columns are Beg / New / Sold, and the per-row End Stock
//    (unchanged) is now the LAST column of the table, after all months,
//    instead of pinned next to Size — this keeps the sticky Size column
//    as the only frozen column and, combined with a fixed table layout /
//    percentage column widths, lets the whole table fit inside the
//    drawer on a normal desktop viewport without horizontal scrolling:
//      Beg  = stock as of the start of that month (unchanged).
//      ADJ  = net of ALL stock_ledger quantity entries in that exact
//             month, positive AND negative (stock-in, incoming/outgoing
//             transfers, adjustments — everything nets together). This
//             was previously "New" and counted inbound (positive) entries
//             only; it's now a genuine net-adjustment figure, so it can
//             show negative months.
//      Sold = units sold in that exact month (unchanged).
//      Stock (end) = stock as of Month Period's end (unchanged values,
//             just relocated to the end of the row).
//    A final "Suggested Restock" column (per size, plus a product total)
//    now follows Stock: peakMonthlySales (that size's single best month
//    of sales within the displayed 6-month window) minus its current
//    (end) stock, floored at 0, plus a fixed +1 unit buffer — 0/blank
//    when current stock already covers the peak month. This is the same
//    per-variant opportunity figure that drives Need Restock's sort
//    below, just with the +1 buffer added for the actual restock
//    suggestion (the buffer is NOT included in the sort score).
//
// STICKY COLUMN WIDTH: the frozen first column (item label) in the
//    Model/Product/Variant tables and the Rising/Declining lists is capped
//    at a fixed max-width with ellipsis truncation (full text still
//    available via native title-tooltip on hover) — a long "CODE — Product
//    Name" label was pushing the data columns out of view on the Product
//    table especially. Applied to every sticky-column table in this file
//    for consistency, not just Sales by Product.
//
// RISING/DECLINING FORMULA (unchanged from before): drop any of the 5
//    months before Month Period that had 0 sales, average what's left as
//    the baseline (skip the row entirely if there's no non-zero prior
//    month at all), gain = chosen month − that average. Rising = positive
//    gain desc. Declining = negative gain, most negative first. Ranked by
//    absolute unit gain (pcs), not percentage.
//
// NEED RESTOCK — MISSED SALES OPPORTUNITY SCORE (replaces the old
//    sales6mo × (1 + oosStreak) importance score): for each VARIANT under
//    a product, take that variant's single best month of sales within the
//    displayed 6-month window (peakMonthlySales), subtract its current
//    (end-of-Month-Period) stock, and floor at 0 — a variant that's
//    already stocked at or above its own peak demand contributes nothing.
//    Sum that across every variant of the product; that sum is the
//    product's uncapped opportunity, representing the most additional
//    sales this product plausibly left on the table by being
//    under-stocked. That sum is then CAPPED by a second figure, Highest
//    Monthly Sales — the biggest single month the WHOLE product (all
//    variants combined) actually did within the window: if that
//    realistic ceiling is lower than the summed opportunity, the score
//    uses the ceiling instead (each variant's own peak may have landed in
//    a different month, so the summed figure can overstate what the
//    product could really do in any one month). Products scoring 0
//    (every variant already covers its own peak) are dropped from the
//    list entirely — there's no restock upside to show. No OOS
//    requirement and no top-30 candidate-pool pre-filter anymore — every
//    product with history is considered; the score itself is the filter.
//    Sort is this (capped) score, descending.
//
// ASSUMPTIONS (confirm / correct if wrong) — carried over:
//   - OOS threshold is stock <= 0 throughout.
//   - Stock reference point is the END of Month Period, not today's real
//     date.
//   - "Products/models with history" = at least one store_sales or
//     stock_ledger record at this store.
//   - Need Restock no longer uses a candidate pool or OOS requirement —
//     every product with history is scored, and only score > 0 survives
//     the filter (see MISSED SALES OPPORTUNITY SCORE above).
//   - Product Rotation's minimum-trial "start selling" date = the
//     earliest of that product's store_sales OR stock_ledger records
//     (i.e. when it first showed up at this store at all), not strictly
//     its first actual sale — a product that's had zero sales across a
//     full 3-month trial is exactly the case Rotation should surface, so
//     gating on "first sale" alone would wrongly exclude it. Flag it if
//     you wanted the stricter "first sale only" definition instead.
//   - Sticky column max-width is 220px, arbitrary but reasonable — easy
//     to adjust if it's cutting off codes that need more room in
//     practice.
//   - NEW: the drill-down drawer's "New" column is renamed "ADJ" and now
//     nets ALL stock_ledger.quantity entries in that month (positive and
//     negative), instead of summing positive (inbound) entries only —
//     flag it if you wanted it split back into separate in/out figures.
//   - NEW: Product Rotation also excludes products that are currently out
//     of stock (end-of-Month-Period stock <= 0) — there's nothing to
//     "drop" from a product that's already gone; Rotation is meant to
//     surface poor sellers that are still tying up shelf space/inventory.
//   - NEW: drill-down drawer widths were widened (product mode 700→960,
//     model mode 860→1040) to give the now-fixed-layout table enough
//     room on desktop; if your typical screen is narrower than ~1300px
//     you may still see the browser's own scrollbar for the drawer
//     itself (not the table) — flag it and I'll size it responsively
//     instead of with fixed px.
//   - NEW: mobile (≤640px) responsive pass, via a single injected <style>
//     tag (RESPONSIVE_STYLE) using a 'mreport-' class prefix so it won't
//     clash with other jblocks on the same page:
//       • Need Restock / Product Rotation cards: the right-hand stat
//         block (Opportunity/Stock/Last Mo./6 Mo.) and badges shrink
//         (smaller gap/font) instead of overflowing.
//       • The drill-down drawer's per-size table switches OFF its
//         desktop fixed/percentage column layout (which exists purely to
//         avoid horizontal scroll on desktop) and instead gets a fixed
//         min-width with normal auto column sizing, so text stays
//         readable and the table scrolls horizontally instead of
//         squishing.
//       • Sales by Product: the item cell switches from one truncated
//         line to two wrapped lines (code, then name) so the name isn't
//         clipped on a narrow screen; Model/Variant tables are unchanged.
//     640px is a reasonable phone-width guess — flag it if you want the
//     breakpoint adjusted.
//
// KNOWN LIMITATION (carried over): fetchStores()/fetchSalesRows()/
// fetchLedgerRows() still use ctx.sql (admin/root-gated, silently empty
// for non-admin roles). Only fetchImages() is on the resource API.
//
// Depends on: none.
